ong>Genital Herpes<\\/strong><\\/p><p>A virus that causes sores on sex organ or mouth.<\\/p><p>Skin to skin contact even when there are no symptoms.<\\/p><p>After 5-21 days, there are small, painful sores that will go away. They may itch, burn, tingle or ooze. Sore reappear later.<\\/p><p>NO Cure. Treatments lessen symptoms and help prevent recurrence.<\\/p><p>Pay attention to outbreaks and sores. Avoid contact as much as possible.<\\/p><p><strong>Genital Warts<\\/strong><\\/p><p><strong>(HPV)<\\/strong><\\/p><p>A virus that infects the sex organs and causes warts or bumps, some very small.<\\/p><p>Contact with warts.<\\/p><p>After many months, small, painless bumps appear on the genitals or anal area.<\\/p><p>NO Cure. Warts are removed through different methods.<\\/p><p>Pay attention to warts around someone\\u2019s penis\\/vagina, anus and genital area.<\\/p><p><strong>Gonorrhea<\\/strong><\\/p><p>Bacteria that can infect the urethra (opening of your penis), throat, anus or testicles.<\\/p><p>Oral, vaginal or anal sex without protection.<\\/p><p>After 3-5 days, there is a smelly discharge or burning, particularly when urinating.<\\/p><p>Antibiotics<\\/p><p>Pay attention to any odors. Use condoms for anal and vaginal sex.<\\/p><p><strong>Hepatitis A<\\/strong><\\/p><p>A virus that causes inflammation of the liver.<\\/p><p>Orally transmitted. Sharing silverware or toothbrushes, eating contaminated food, or oral-to-anal contact with an infected person.<\\/p><p>After 10-50 days, there is fever, abdominal pain, nausea and fatigue.<\\/p><p>NO Cure. May take 6-12 months to resolve and is rarely fatal.<\\/p><p>Get vaccinated. Use a latex barrier for anal and vaginal contact.<\\/p><p><strong>Hepatitis B<\\/strong><\\/p><p>A virus that causes inflammation of the liver. May lead to cancer or cirrhosis.<\\/p><p>Contact with infected blood or bodily fluids, unprotected anal sex or sharing needles with an infected person.<\\/p><p>After 60-90 days, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, yellowing of skin and eyes, dark urine.<\\/p><p>NO Cure. Liver infection can become chronic and sometimes be fatal.<\\/p><p>Get vaccinated. Use a latex barrier for anal and vaginal contact.<\\/p><p><strong>Hepatitis C<\\/strong><\\/p><p>A virus that causes a more serious inflammation of the liver and liver failure over time.<\\/p><p>Contact with infected blood or bodily fluids, unprotected anal sex or sharing needles.<\\/p><p>After 60-90 days, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, but mostly no symptoms.<\\/p><p>NO Cure or vaccine. High chance of becoming chronic or fatal.<\\/p><p>Don\\u2019t share needles. Use a condom for anal and vaginal sex.<\\/p><p><strong>HIV<\\/strong><\\/p><p>A virus that attacks the immune system.<\\/p><p>Unprotected anal and vaginal sex, sharing needles.<\\/p><p>Get an HIV test. During the first weeks: flu-like symptoms, fever, night sweats, weight loss, sore\\/swollen lymph nodes occur. After some years, people may develop illnesses, infections, and cancers (AIDS diagnosis).<\\/p><p>NO Cure or vaccine. HIV treatments help many people with HIV\\/AIDS to live longer and healthier lives.<\\/p><p>Don\\u2019t share needles. Use a condom for anal and vaginal sex.<\\/p><p><strong>Lympho-granuloma<\\/strong><\\/p><p><strong>venereum<\\/strong><\\/p><p>A bacterial infection that can cause ulcers on the penis or anus.<\\/p><p>Anal or oral sex \\u2013 unprotected anal intercourse is a common risk factor.<\\/p><p>Within 30 days, pimple or blister turns into ulcer. Painful lymph nodes, anal discharge, bloody diarrhea.<\\/p><p>Three weeks of uninterrupted antibiotics.<\\/p><p>Use a condom for anal and vaginal sex. Pay attention to any open sores.<\\/p><p><strong>Syphilis<\\/strong><\\/p><p>A bacteria that causes a chancre sore on butt, penis or mouth. Untreated, it spreads throughout the body.<\\/p><p>Oral or anal sex without protection. Contact with sores.<\\/p><p>After 3 weeks, sores on genitals or mouth rash, swollen glands and fever.<\\/p><p>Antibiotics<\\/p><p>Use a condom for anal and vaginal sex. Pay attention to any open sores.<\\/p><p>***It is important to always use a condom properly!***<br><\\/p><h4>For persons whose sexual behaviors place them at risk for HIV and STI\'s, correct and consistent use of a condom can reduce the risk of HIV and STI transmission. However, no protective method is 100% effective, and condom use cannot guarantee absolute protection against any STI\'s.<\\/h4>\"}}}}}', '2015-06-07 04:11:14', '2015-06-07 04:11:14', '933d3843-fb6b-4760-8810-2c5df2267902');
